sec.p:
The production of biomass to meet the energy needs of humanity without competing with food production should prioritize the production of fibrous plants, instead of starch and oilseed plants [18]. Fibrous plants bring several advantages and fit well within the requirements deemed important to be elected as producers of biomass. From the work of Hill et al. [9], Rubin [11], Sticklen [12],[18], Coombs [22], and Schmer et al. [25], the following characteristics may be listed:
Plants of high transforming efficiency, that is, high processing capacity of solar energy into biomass with the less possible amount of water, nutrients, and other direct and indirect inputs (for example, workforce from planting to harvest) (C4 plants);
Perennial but fast growth and long-term canopy to allow harvest during most of the year;
Possibility of application of agricultural technology in large-scale production;
Easily and efficiently processed into usable forms of energy, and;
Sustainable economically and environmentally: adapted to suboptimal environments to not compete with food production at the same time that requires less energy input, thus bringing marginal lands into production with its all social-benefit consequences; high positive rate of carbon (C) balance, etc.

The use of biomass fiber as a raw material for energy purposes can be done according to four basic platforms:
Direct combustion to produce thermal energy (steam) and electric power (cogeneration);
Chemical or enzymatic hydrolysis of fiber (cellulose and hemicellulose) to obtain fermentable sugars and production of liquid fuels;
Gasification to produce synthesis gas (carbon monoxide and hydrogen) or generation of biogas, and;
Pyrolysis to produce bio-oil or coal/coke.
